I"<p>When automatically configuring <a class="internal-link" href="/secondbrain/notes-flashcards-and-background-describe-previous-knowledge">flashcards</a> for language learning, itâ€™s trivial to create prompts which <a class="internal-link" href="/secondbrain/concept-learning-is-few-shot-scaffolding-supported-by-working-memory">only contain one unknown word</a>. However, multi-word expressions or n-grams (e.g. idioms, typical noun phrases) are self-contained and already <a class="internal-link" href="/secondbrain/second-brain-faces-atomic-debt">atomic</a>. In light of this, <a class="internal-link" href="/secondbrain/natural-language-understanding-segments-text-into-thoughts">segmentation</a> of unknown structures goes beyond the word level and is non-trivial.</p>
